How are the Taiwanese servicing their credit card debt?

This notebook will explore what characterizes Taiwanese credit card debt holders. The data has been downloaded from kaggele at: https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/default-of-credit-card-clients-dataset.

We would like to acknowledge Lichman, M. (2013). UCI Machine Learning Repository [http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml]. Irvine, CA: University of California, School of Information and Computer Science.

The original dataset can be found at the UCI Machine Learning Repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/default+of+credit+card+clients

Problem statement

By exploring the some demographic data matched with data on credit card debt it is possible to get, at least an rough, idea of the kind od people collecting credit card debt; what is their educational backgrond? How old are they? What is their marritial status? And at least are they male or female?

We are going to run both a regression problem and a classification problem. The regression problem will be on predicting the age of a credit card debt holder. The regression problem will not be very extensive since it is not the main focus point of this notebook.

The classification problem will be on predicting whether a credit card debt holder default on the credit or not. For the classification problem we will run several models since this will be the focal point of this notebook. If you browse through some of the links above you will see that the use of the dataset have been used for classification problems (see also the collecting the data for the purpose of the dataset).

Collecting the data

The credit card issuer has gathered information on 30000 customers. The dataset contains information on 24 variables, including demographic factors, credit data, history of payment, and bill statements of credit card customers from April 2005 to September 2005, as well as information on the outcome: did the customer default or not? We had problems reading the full dataset with 30000 observations therefore we have done some datacleaning before loading the data. We removed values from pay_0 through pay_6 with values of -2 and 0 since these have no assigned values. This leaves us with 4057 observations.

This gives insight into whether a customer is likely to default or not.

Dimentionality reduction.

Now we will look at Principal Component Analysis (PCA) which takes possible correlated variables and turn them into linear uncorrelated variables.

library(FactoMineR)
library(factoextra)
res.pca <- PCA(credit_df, scale.unit = TRUE, graph = FALSE)

Now we will illustrate what component and to what degree that component explains the variance using a scree plot.

fviz_screeplot(res.pca, 
               addlabels = TRUE, 
               ncp = 10, 
               ggtheme = theme_gray())

It is clear from the Scree plot that the first component explains most of the variance just as we expected.

Lets see if we can use our ndimentional reductions to differentiate groups based on the whether an individual will default payment next month or not.

credit_df %<>%
  mutate(default = ifelse(default.payment.next.month > mean(default.payment.next.month), TRUE, FALSE))
fviz_pca_biplot(res.pca,
                alpha.ind = "cos2",
                geom = "point", 
                habillage = factor(credit_df$default.payment.next.month),
                addEllipses = TRUE,
                ggtheme = theme_gray())

So we get two clusters based on default payment. There are some overlapping between the groups but it looks like there is a strong devision from upper left to lower right.

Now lets move on to do some unsupervised machine learning using clustering.

Clustering

Now that we have some basic relationships illustrated it is time to start clustering to see how the individuals group together. We will use k-means clustering.

First up lets take a look at how many clusters we need to make this happen.

So how many clusters are we going to use?

fviz_nbclust(scale(credit_df), 
            kmeans, 
            method = "wss")

We will go with 3 clusters.

Now setting the right row names otherwise the next dplyr pipe will delete them again.

rownames(credit_df) <- credit_df %>% pull(id)

Only choosing the data we want to cluster. In this case we use all the variables from the data set.

km <- kmeans(scale(credit_df), centers = 3, nstart = 20)  
km.credit <- kmeans(credit_df %>% select(-id) %>% scale(), centers = 3)

Now visualize the data.

library(factoextra)
fviz_cluster(km.credit, 
             data = credit_df %>% select(-id) %>% scale())

Seems like 3 clusters are optimal.

Now binding to original credit data.

Binding to original data.

credit_df <- credit_df %>%
  bind_cols(cluster = km.credit$cluster)

Now lets take a quick look at how many individuals are in the different clusters.

credit_df %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  count()

So most people in cluster 1 followed by cluster 3 and least people ind cluster 2. Lets take a look what characterizes cluster 1 - and also the other two clusters.

credit_df %>%
  bind_cols(cluster = km$cluster) %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  mutate(n = n()) %>%
  summarise_all(funs(mean))

Remember this is average scores for the given variables.

Most people in cluster 1 with an average credit card debt of 203.435 NTD. More women than men (closer to 2 than 1). In cluster 1 people are most likely to be married and for all months they are on average likely to be on point with their repayment scheme and are not very likely to default (closer to 0 than 1).

Cluster 3 is most likely to default which makes sense since people in that cluster have the largest bill throughout all months and they are on average a little more than two months behind on their payments in all months.

Now lets take a look at individuals based on different restrictions being met or not.

credit_df %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  arrange() %>%
  group_by(id, default.payment.next.month) %>%
  summarize(total = n(),
            gender = mean(sex == 1), #Man or woman?
            education = mean(education < 3), #What about the highly educated?
            marriage = mean(marriage == 1)) %>%
  ungroup()

Please be adviced that since we have now set up some restriction of e.g.Â gender, 1 means the condition is met and the id is male but 0 means condition is not met and therefore the person is a woman (not = 2 here as in the data frame).

Machine learning

Regression

So for this regreesion problem we are trying to predict age. Why is that intersting? Well, it is interesting to know if it is possible to predict when you are likely to take on credit card debt. That way it is possibly easier for you to avoid taking on (expensive) credit card debt in the first place. If you are in your mid twenties using this prediction will allow you to get an idea of when to be aware of your consumption and maybe even save up for your future expenses you would otherwise finance with credit card.

We tried different regressions models and found elastic net to give the best results.

First up is setting training and test sets using af 80/20 split.

library(caret)
index <- createDataPartition(y = credit_df %>% pull(age), p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
training <- credit_df[index,]
test <- credit_df[-index,]

Some further preprocessing is made.

library(recipes)
reci <- recipe(age ~ ., data = training) %>%
  step_center(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  step_scale(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  prep(data = training)

We will now allot the outcom and predictors in training and test set.

# Training: split in y and x
x_train <-bake(reci, newdata = training) %>% select(-age) 
y_train <- training %>% pull(age)
# test: split in y and x
x_test <-bake(reci, newdata = test) %>% select(-age) 
y_test <- test %>% pull(age)

Remove what we dont need anymore.

rm(index, reci)

Crossvalidating the training data.

Setting number of crosvalidations (CV) to 10.

ctrl.reg <- trainControl(method = "cv", 
                           number = 10)

The best model fron the extended verison was the elastic net.

The elastic net model has the functional form of af generilized linear model meaning it is a flexible generalization of a linear model which means the magnitude of the variance to be a function of its own prediction.

tune.glmnet = expand.grid(alpha = seq(0, 1, length = 5), 
                          lambda = seq(0, 1, length = 5))

Fitting the model.

fit.glmnet <- train(x = x_train, 
                    y = y_train, 
                    trControl = ctrl.reg, 
                    method = "glmnet", family = "gaussian", 
                    tuneGrid = tune.glmnet)

Classification

Next up we present a classification problem where we want to predict wheter an individual default on their credit card debt (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

First off we have to change some variable types to make sure that the code will run and read the default value correct.

str(credit_df$default)
 logi [1:4057] FALSE TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE ...
credit_df$default <- as.factor(as.logical(credit_df$default))
str(credit_df$default)
 Factor w/ 2 levels "FALSE","TRUE": 1 2 1 1 1 1 2 1 1 2 ...
levels(credit_df$default) <- make.names(levels(factor(credit_df$default)))

This short version only shows the best performer: Random Forest.

First up is setting training and test sets using af 80/20 split setting p = .8. It is important to do this to be able to create a model based on training data and then use that model on the test data. It is important to know the test data before hand to make sure how accurate the prediction is. If we did not have the test data we would not have the possiblity to properbly assesst he prediction on new data.

library(caret)
index <- createDataPartition(y = credit_df %>% pull(default), p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
training <- credit_df[index,] %>% select(-default.payment.next.month)
test <- credit_df[-index,] %>% select(-default.payment.next.month)

Some further preprocessing is made.

As a last step we also remove features with zero-variance.

library(recipes)
reci <- recipe(default ~ ., data = training) %>%
  step_center(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  step_scale(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  prep(data = training)

We will now allot the outcom and predictors in training and test set. This is done to ease the workflow later on.

# Training: split in y and x
x_train <-bake(reci, newdata = training) %>% select(-default) 
y_train <- training %>% pull(default)
# test: split in y and x
x_test <-bake(reci, newdata = test) %>% select(-default) 
y_test <- test %>% pull(default)

Remove what we dont need anymore.

rm(index, reci)

Crossvalidating the training data.

Setting number og crosvalidations (CV) to 10.
